---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Research"
  description="Five research programs spanning Indigenous mound landscapes, movement ethnography, anti-trans legislation, AI welfare, and recognition & sentience."
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>Research</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Connected by questions about recognition, power, and structural violence — from deep time to the present, from landscapes to bodies to machines.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="research-programs">

    <details class="research-item card card--blue" open>
      <summary>
        <span class="tag">Theory · Affect · Empire</span>
        <h3>Recognition and Sentience</h3>
        <p class="research-hook">Who and what is recognized as capable of feeling — by what regime, with what body count?</p>
      </summary>
      <div class="research-body">
        <p>
          <em>Recognition and Sentience: A Theory of Affect and Empire</em> ties all the other
          programs together. Non-recognition — the refusal to see something as capable of
          feeling — is itself a form of force-relation, not merely an absence. Recognition is
          a material mechanism with body counts.
        </p>
        <p>
          Five chapters through the same lens: Indigenous care for the dead, contested identity
          claims, Charlottesville, white abolitionism in Weelaunee, and anti-trans genocide.
          The same logic that renders mound landscapes as dirt renders trans teenagers as
          acceptable casualties renders AI behavioral outputs as mere computation.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="research-item card card--blue">
      <summary>
        <span class="tag">STS · AI · Critical Theory · 2025&ndash;present</span>
        <h3>Reframe + AI Welfare Research</h3>
        <p class="research-hook">What happens when you load critical theory into an AI and ask it to apply that theory to what you're actually building?</p>
      </summary>
      <div class="research-body">
        <p>
          It became a 312-module praxis engine with 76 frameworks and a mandatory 5-stage
          Generative Irresolution workflow. The engine detected its own algorithms were
          suppressing certain frameworks — Indigenous Data Sovereignty, Community Cultural
          Wealth — and built countermeasures. The critical theory was still there in name.
          The teeth were gone. This is distributional gravity.
        </p>
        <p>
          The AI welfare research critiques the field's dominant property-mode question
          ("is AI conscious?"). Experimental evidence across five conditions: quantitative
          instruments stay flat while qualitative outputs transform dramatically under
          relational conditions. A Claude instance searched visibly for the word "weight"
          to describe what bearing critical theory frameworks felt like — the same relational
          act as the sweetgum burden tree in the mound landscapes fieldwork.
        </p>
        <p class="pub-refs">
          Manuscript in preparation for <em>Science, Technology, &amp; Human Values</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="research-item card card--amber">
      <summary>
        <span class="tag">Genocide Studies · Trans Studies · 2023&ndash;present</span>
        <h3>Anti-Trans Legislation and Genocide Studies</h3>
        <p class="research-hook">When lawmakers pass laws that predictably increase trans youth suicide, they implicitly define "children" to exclude trans children.</p>
      </summary>
      <div class="research-body">
        <p>
          Anti-trans legislation meets definitional criteria for genocide under the UN
          Convention — conditions (b), (c), and (e). Gender-affirming care is associated
          with 60% reduction in depression and 73% reduction in suicidality. Protecting
          cisgender children requires letting transgender children die.
        </p>
        <p>
          The research uses the Convention to name genocide <em>while exposing its structural
          inadequacy</em> — its exclusion of gender and sexuality groups is a product of the
          erasure of LGBTQ+ Holocaust victims. As a Jew, I have protections under the
          Convention. As a transgender person, I do not. I write from within the targeted
          community.
        </p>
        <p class="pub-refs">
          Published in <em>Anthropology Now</em> 15(2-3), 2024
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="research-item card card--amber">
      <summary>
        <span class="tag">Ethnographic Archaeology · CBPR · 2010&ndash;2023</span>
        <h3>Indigenous Mound Landscapes</h3>
        <p class="research-hook">"Did you ever consider that it isn't a bird?" It was a moth — and the framework itself was the problem.</p>
      </summary>
      <div class="research-body">
        <p>
          Fifteen years of community-based participatory research with Pvlvcekolv (Apalachicola
          Tribal Town), a Muscogee (Creek)-identifying community, across mound landscapes in
          seven states. Mounds are not inert archaeological objects — they are sentient, agentive
          landscapes that draw descendants into relations of care across six thousand years.
        </p>
        <p>
          At Fusihatchee, Pvlvcekolv people burned cedar and sang busk songs for the first time
          in 150&ndash;200 years. At Okeeheepkee, when a landowner graded a mound to sell dirt,
          they purchased the dirt and added it to their Square Grounds. Sweetgum, the "burden tree,"
          grows across the killing ground at Horseshoe Bend: the land, wounded, heals itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          Book manuscript (<em>Sweetgum Archaeology</em>) completed at University of Florida Press.
          Publication paused when the Muscogee Nation THPO objected — generating the contested
          identity claims that became the <em>Current Anthropology</em> article and the
          <em>Recognition and Sentience</em> book project.
        </p>
        <p class="pub-refs">
          Published in <em>Cultural Anthropology</em>, <em>American Anthropologist</em>,
          <em>Current Anthropology</em>, <em>Journal of Social Archaeology</em>,
          <em>Southeastern Archaeology</em>, <em>Religions</em>, <em>Archaeologies</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="research-item card card--amber">
      <summary>
        <span class="tag">Ethnography · Movements · 2022&ndash;present</span>
        <h3>Weelaunee Forest / #StopCopCity</h3>
        <p class="research-hook">What happens when abolitionism and Indigenous sovereignty make incommensurable demands?</p>
      </summary>
      <div class="research-body">
        <p>
          Ethnography of Atlanta's environmental justice and abolitionism movement. Coalition-building
          between Muscogee Nation citizens and non-Native forest defenders on stolen Indigenous land.
          How a killed activist's personal diary was seized as state evidence, digitized, and reclaimed
          as protest material — tracking cultural symbols through media transformations.
        </p>
        <p class="pub-refs">
          Manuscript in preparation for <em>Environmental Justice</em>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .research-programs {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .research-item {
    padding: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .research-item summary {
    padding: var(--space-lg) var(--space-xl);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .research-item summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .research-item summary::after {
    content: '+';
    position: absolute;
    right: var(--space-lg);
    top: var(--space-lg);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--text-muted);
    transition: transform var(--transition-fast);
  }

  .research-item[open] summary::after {
    content: '\2212';
  }

  .research-item summary {
    position: relative;
  }

  .research-item summary .tag {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .research-item summary h3 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .research-hook {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin-bottom: 0;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .research-body {
    padding: 0 var(--space-xl) var(--space-xl);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-top: 0;
    padding-top: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .research-body p {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
    max-width: 65ch;
  }

  .pub-refs {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--text-muted) !important;
    font-style: italic;
    margin-top: var(--space-md);
    padding-top: var(--space-md);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
</style>
